description.text:
======THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS NOT USEABLE YET======

What is this?

This is an attempt at replacing completely the stock carriage of the Anet A8 to make it :
1°) Lighter
2°) Able to carry 2 E3D V6
3°) Keep the exact same places for screws as the original carriage, plus the ones needed for assembly.

To mount this on your Anet A8, you will need :

  • 1x this X axis belt holder : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1666094
  • 4x M5/20 bolts
  • 4x M5 nuts (preferably Nylstop ones)

And the following files from this thing :

  • 1x "Connection plate"
  • 1x "Carriage with dual E3D supports"
  • 1x "Extruder fan duct (choose 40mm or 60mm depending on the size you will use)
  • 1x "Extruder fan mount" (same size as the extruder fan duct)
  • 1x "Clamp" (same size as the extruder fan duct)
  • 1x "Fan splitter"

3 steps for assembly :
1°) Mount the "connection plate" to the bearing blocks with the original M4 screws
2°) Mount the "carriage" to the "connection plate" with the M5x20 bolts and the M5 nuts
3°) Clip your E3D v6 hot ends onto the carriage. They should fit firmly in place.

Changelog

  • 02/06/17
    "Extruder fan support" added to parts list
    "Connection plate" : edited the X axis belt tensioning support screws from 2mm diam to 3mm diam & corrected the lower belt tensioner screw hole position
    "Carriage_with_dual_E3D_V6_supports" : Edited to fix the height of the accessory clamps to 7mm (previously 9mm), and reinforced the clamp arms with chamfers. Also made the pockets bigger to make clearance for the belt tensioner screws.
  • 04/06/17
    Replaced all the files with updated versions
    Included setups for either 40 or 60mm fans
  • 10/06/17
    Deleted some useless files
    Added a new design for the rear print-cooling fan holder and a new fan duct I designed myself too

title: HICTOP Print Bed Thumb Screw - All Plastic

description.text:
This is a simple bed adjustment thumb screw for HICTOP printers. It is threaded and does NOT require an actual metal nut. The design is minimal to allow for clearance around the acrylic pieces on a HICTOP printer. It's also a work in progress. :-)

If this design doesn't fit around the ends of your printer, please let me know where and by how much and I'll add another design.

As well, please see the printing notes regarding size.

Printer:

HICTOP 3DP-17

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

10%

Notes:

Printing threading holes of such small sizes is challenging, and this model is sized for my printer. I'm currently using a 0.3mm nozzle which may play a part in the sizing of this model.

Before using it, I would suggest screwing an M3 screw all the way through to clean out any excess plastic and to make sure the printed threads are not too tight and not too loose.

I would also suggest printing a single one first to check the size of the screw hole. An M3 screw should screw in easily with the threads built into the model. If it does not, I recommend using your slicer's horizontal size adjustments which "pull in" or "push out" the walls of a model. To increase the size of the screw hole you would use a NEGATIVE adjustment as you want the walls of the hole to be pulled into the model and the hole made larger.

If the hole is too loose, you could use a positive number to push out the walls of the hole. However, this would also push out the outer walls of the thumb screw, increasing its diameter and potentially make it not have clearance at the ends of the Y axis. You may instead wish to use a negative value in your slicer's scale function for the X and Y axis. (IE. Don't use "uniform scaling.") This will shrink the whole model on the X/Y plane, making the hole smaller. It is important to not scale the Z axis as this will change the pitch of the printed threads and make them useless.

I may tweak the size of the hole in the future. This is a work in progress. :-)

This is a smartphone tapping device attached to a servo horn. Styluses like these [ http://a.co/htD1zzX ] are plugged into one or both of the side holes. The styli should be grounded somehow, I've found that running an unbent paperclip between both styluses seems to work, but I'm sure there's a less awkward way.

A version of the Bre Pettis Polhemus scan reduced to a low polygon state, after which I've outlined the polygon edges with boxes to form a lattice geometry from the original structure. This was done with my Modelbuilder Processing library, specifically with UGeometry.loadSTL() and UPrimitive.box2points(). The output is a mess of overlapping meshes, which must be cleaned up in Netfabb or similar. Download BreTest01 LoLoPoly.stl if you want to see the low-poly STL that was used as input.

This should print fine at medium size on a Replicator. At lower sizes the lattice "columns" become too thin, and will break during printing. I'm not sure how this will print on a Thingomatic, but the walls don't have so many gaps so it might just work.

description.text:
Wanted a noise maker for my son's soccer games, and found a few of these sirens here. I made a hand cranked one, but never turned fast enough to make the noise. I combined the design of 2 sirens and added some of my own ideas, and came up with this. You can see the 2 things that inspired me in the remix section.

There is a video for assembling this thing, should be pretty simple. https://youtu.be/H9kh328obUw
And there is a video of the thing in action. https://youtu.be/Hl_q7HTXwfI
It is fairly noisy... let's say it would get annoying to be waken up by this... but, really, for a soccer game, amongst the other noise makers, it is really not extremely noisy. Anyways... my son completely forbid be from bringing it at any match :(

You will have to purchase a few items. I had them all in stock from RC planes and drones, but most people don't have these things handy, so here's the list of things to get (really, I don't expect many people to print this... it gets reasonably pricey for what it is!):

-https://hobbyking.com/en_us/afro-race-spec-mini-20amp-multi-rotor-speed-controller-with-bec.html (13 can$)
-https://hobbyking.com/en_us/a20-22l-920kv-brushless-outrunner.html (10 can$)
-https://hobbyking.com/en_us/hobbykingtm-servo-tester.html (4.65 can$)
-1 bearing like this: http://www.ebay.ca/itm/SKF-625-2Z-DEEP-GROOVE-BALL-BEARING-5mm-x-16mm-x-5mm-FIT-C0-DBL-SEAL-/131878598342?hash=item1eb493b6c6 (4.30 can$)
-Battery: you can buy any lipo 3S battery at your hobby shop, but for reference I had this one at home: https://hobbyking.com/en_us/turnigy-nano-tech-1500mah-3s-35-70c-lipo-pack.html (13 can$).

If you need to buy all that, it's 45$ total.

If you need help with the connections, send me a message and I'll help you out.

You print 1 of each file, except the handle pin, you need 2. And the screws, you need 5.

The only thing I feel I need to add now, is that the small pin has a hole in it... I took a nail that fit the size (well, I made the hole to fit the nail i had), cut it to the length of the pin, and inserted it in the hole. That way, the pin will never break. You could modify the pin hole size to accommodate a nail you already have at home.

title: Eachine E011/E010 FPV Super Mini Light AIO Camera Mount - OpenSCAD - Customizable

description.text:
Update: 2017-06-09
After cracking the top off the lens protectors from many hard crashes I have re-printed the design in Nylon! (previously PETG) it seems basically indestructible now! I recommend everyone get a roll of nylon filament (I used Esun ePA) if they can, printing with the same settings as PETG = 250C hotend, 80C bed, 80mm/s. I have also updated a slightly modified copy of the source files, some optimizations to base height and wire hole position are included. I have also modified my E011 with an additional battery connector soldered on the top back so it can use either type.

The lens protectors do not obstruct the camera field of view, but provide some nice crash protection.

I had one of my lenses break off the PCB on these cameras before adding the lens guards. When the camera costs as much as the whole copter I think .3 gram extra for the lens guards is worth it ;) (mount was .7g before adding guards). They are easy to comment out in OpenSCAD if you would like to remove them.

I would suggest everyone de-solder the circular polarized antenna and just use a short ~15mm length of stranded wire for a simple dipole antenna.. Ideally the correct 5.8ghz 1/4 wavelength but it seems to work fine without exact measurements. I have had good success with video reception with this type of antenna and it puts much less stress on the PCB with less chance of the copter being caught on things. I put a piece of clear heat-shrink over the antenna wire to help keep it springy and upright, but it works without that. The stock antenna weighs .9g so right there you've basically covered the weight of this mount.

I have added many variables for different parts of the design, open it up in OpenSCAD or the Customizer app in Thingiverse and play around with changing them if it doesn't fit your camera perfectly and post the result as a remix.

Current dimensions are for this camera: https://www.banggood.com/Super-Mini-Light-AIO-5_8G-48CH-200mW-VTX-520TVL-14-Cmos-FPV-Camera-PALNTSC-for-QX90-QX95-p-1095683.html?p=V9061370462720140842

I suspect the mount will also work with E010(6mm motor but same hole pattern) and Bwhoop model(rebrand of E011) which I believe is using the same chassis/motors as the Eachine E011

description.text:
This print is ready to go and does not need any more fixing to be printed!

3D Print other RWBY models here:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2357481 Ruby Rose
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2397963 Weiss Schnee

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2753068 Nora

Join the Anime Figure group and share and print anime figures! As well as Updates on what im doing next https://www.thingiverse.com/groups/animefigures
Support me on Patreon! https://www.patreon.com/AnimuAnimu/posts

This print already has all the support material ready to go, DO NOT add SUPPORT MATERIAL.
the support material that i already added to the file has tapered ends and easily breaks off, however be very careful removing, especially around the head. no cutting or gluing necessary.
DO NOT PRINT WITH A RAFT OR SUPPORT MATERIAL

there are THREE stl files included, PRINT THE 3DPrintReady FILE. I included files of the print without supports and one without the base if you want to add your own supports. note a base is necessary or the model will tip over.

it is a good idea to add some pauses toward the tip of the sickle so that the point has enough time to cool and doesnt end up all melted like mine

i included my Cura print settings if you were curious, however you should switch to like a .05 mm layer height and a slower print speed to make it look better. if i get around to it, ill print it again at slower speed and post more pictures. i printed mine kind of fast.

i did a bunch of smoothing in Meshmixer, so the stl file is quite big even after being 'reduced' so be patient!

i only had black PLA on hand, im sure a white plastic will make the details show up better, especially in pictures. and wont leave white spots where the support material attatched.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

No

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

30% this is critical that you make it at least 30 percent

Notes:

I printed this on a monoprice maker select plus (a rebrand of the wanhao, identical printer)
if you want to speed up print time, keep the outer layer slow, so it looks good, but increase the fill print speed.

IMPORTANT: you MUST have AT LEAST a .8mm shell thickness or the supports will fuse with the model!

i included all my Cura print settings in the images
just a pliers and a flush cut to remove any stringing and the break-away supports. be carful removing supports, the model has many detailed and thin features.

this is a scan of an MMD model that i edited and made print ready with pmx editor and meshmixer. i also did a lot of smoothing, the scan had sharp polynomials and edges. the sickle and Ruby were separate models so aligning the prop was a little tricky. i also quickly made a base for it in SolidWorks

comments.text:
most of the supports are my standard 3mm wide, and should fare okay, but a few smaller details, like the hair on her left hand side are supported by thinner supports that might not work too good. but if you have your retraction settings dialed in, and a strong enough fan than it should work.
the top of the sickle is what im more worried about, because it is fragile at standard size due to the layers being so small that they dont have enough time to cool properly and it starts turning into a gooey mess. in your cura settings, or slicer of choice, you should change the print speed above her head to like 10mm/s or slower to solve this.
you do this in cura by going to the plugins tab > Tweak at Z > then tell it to modify the speed

This is an improved version of my earlier power supply cover using Molex connectors. As most has remained the same, I only dwell on the improvements relative to the initial version:
  • An air flow grid on the lower front side allows for better ventilation.
  • The Molex connector can now be secured with clips so that they don't have to be glued in.
  • A new cut-out is provided for the voltage adjustment trimpot.
    • Given that we already have the digital voltmeter to show the exact voltage, I though that it would be neat if I could also fine-tune the voltage directly without removing the cover. For this I unsoldered the 1k trimpot from the power supply PCB and replaced it by a 2-pin header. I then mounted the trimpot onto a little peace of prototype PCB and glued it to the new cut-out to the right of the voltage display. However this kind of modding implies opening up the power supply, which voids your warranty and is potentially dangerous - thus, it should only be done by people who know what they are doing and can take responsibility for it!!! For every one else, I recommend to leave the trimpot where it is and to use the provided blind cover to fill the unused cut-out. For more details, please refer to the description of the initial version of this project. UPDATE 2014-08-28: I just uploaded SCAD and STL files which are especially adapted to Tamiya connectors instead of the Molex connectors. Given the form of the Tamiya connectors, they are hold in place with a screw-on small inner frame which holds the connectors in place. Update 2017-10-24: I just uploaded a 3rd version of this project which has a separate car fuse holder for each of the power outlets, so that each attached device can be protected with a separate blade fuse of the proper value.

I print using ABS with a 0.4mm nozzle using 0.25mm layer height and 0.56mm extrusion width.
Note that the Molex clips are quit thin. I needed to print them without any extra shells to make sure that they are solidly filled.

Background History First
About a month ago.. I was about :the half of my peanut butter toast when my wife mentioned me that my older son has selected his subject for his third grade presentation... Tornado! Seriously! That's great... That kind of subject spark my interest...

So I went here to find something kick-ass to spice up his presentation, I've found a pretty cool tornado vase... So i start printing it... I was looking at my print starting up, finishing my toast (lol)... And my brain was already at the next step... This looks great... But.... It's so... Passive...

So i went back, and i remembered playing with bottle and tornado coupler when a was a youngster... Great found that one and start the print on another printer... Ok now the bad news... I didn't drink soft drink so 2L bottle didn't exist at home... Humm ok, that's right... You could be surprised what I'm ready to do in the name of science ;)

I went back to ask my wife to buy some 2l bottle fill with any liquid , after giving explanation why i leave the table as.... She agreed to add those to the groceries list...

So i go to work... But you know... My brain was working over that... Traffic jam are a great reason to go in my wonderful alternative reality lol

So I made a great kit... Right?... Great, yes! But not awesome... Need to add some mad scientific stuff...

So I search and didn't find something that would fill my needs...Tornado + motor = awesome!

So ... I fired my freecad!

design details
This as been designed to be affordable as possible... About 20$ and that includes at least 2L of your favorite soft drinks ;)

Basic system need a 5-10$ ultrasonic mist generator 24v, and a 50-60mm 24v centrifugal computer fan and a cheap standard on-off rocker switch ...

Since my 24v fan and my cheap PWM pot didn't find their way to my home in time...I was forced to create that "CSL Editdion" (Chinese Shipping Latency Edition). Currently i use a 60mm 12v fan... Since i was forced to take down the voltage to 24 to 12 v I've used an lm317, some resistor and a pot that enable the operator to play with wind speed...

This design as been build with 150x150mm delta in mind... So almost any 3d printer could print that project...

Please Note: This is the first release.... post printing explanation in progress so stay tuned ;)

end of story
So after countless hours of printing and prototyping... I've got that working design... Which work really well...

I'm not equipped with professional photographer rig... And droplet of water lighten by led seems to saturate camera sensor... So pictures or video of the tornado are all over exposed... But no issue up to now with human eyes... It looks great if you use your bare eyes to look at it ;)

I've holded this design until my kid completed his presentation... You know people with 3d printer have tendency to hide between normal people...lol ... Would be a nightmare if other kid in is classroom show up with the same kickass tornado generator... Lol

Be warn: the hardest part of that project was to successfully convince the teacher that my kid designed this by himself... Just joking :D

Hope it would be useful for you... Also it make a great room humidifier :)

Print Using Loose Coils of Filament

I designed wings to attach to a metal can to keep the filament from sliding off the side when printing loose/sample filament coils using the included spool holder on my Original Prusa i3 Mk2. It features a circular cutout in the base in order to stay upright on the arm of the original spool holder.

Usage

To use this spool holder accessory, remove both ends and empty your 14.5oz. can. Then print out the model and simply snap it over the lip at the edge of the can - making sure to be careful and not get cut on any sharp spots around the edge of the can. I've had no issues with only a single wing as long as I always wrap the end fed into the extruder on the side with the wing, but you may want to print two. At this point, you can easily drop a sample coil of filament onto the can and put the can on the normal spool holder, making sure to seat the cutout on top of the standard nubs that you'd rest your spool on so that it doesn't roll off.

multi- digital fabrication machine for the studio(â€¦hence the name: studio.FAB)
some of the functions Iâ€™m including in the design:
_3D printing
_CNC/milling
_thin material cutting (fabric, vinyl, paper, cardboard, etc)
_plotter for inks, paints, graphite now I know a lot of the all-in-one devices fall victim to the â€œjack-of-all-trades-but-master-of-noneâ€ syndrome (Iâ€™m looking at the bloated printerscannercopier thatâ€™s sitting on Robinâ€™s deskâ€¦). thatâ€™s why the studio.FAB isnâ€™t exactly an all-in-one machine â€“ instead, itâ€™s more of a modular design that allows you to quickly and easily (â€¦and Iâ€™m emphasizing that quick and easy part) switch the appropriate parts for the kind of making you want the machine to do. for example, if you want to move from 3D printing to CNC milling, it shouldnâ€™t take you more than 10min. to swap out the belts and pulleys for a lead screw. the studio.FAB is based on the open source RepRap platform. Iâ€™m using 25mm extruded aluminum (t-slot) for the structural framework because itâ€™s more stable and rigid than using threaded rod. also, Iâ€™m designing it with an inverted-T structure (shared by other machines like the Aluminum Mendel, Rook, and Brian Blantonâ€™s unnamed printer) â€“ I think this makes it much easier to upgrade and swap out components when moving from one fabrication method to another (also: easier access to all the parts for repairs.)
one key difference b/w studio.FAB and most of the other machines Iâ€™ve seen is how linear motion is handled. the majority standard is to use a combination of smooth rods and bearings to get smooth motion, but (esp. on longer rods) smooth rods can flex, bend, and get out of alignment. Iâ€™ve designed the studio.FAB to use the much less flexible t-slot as the linear bearing. this is less critical when printing plastic, but can be an issue in subtractive processes like milling. Iâ€™ve been making steady progress, and right now Iâ€™m close to having all the core structural elements designed and built. Iâ€™ve had to design all the parts from scratch; even when Iâ€™ve had to reverse-engineer some derivative designs that use a different size t-slot, I found different solutions that seem to work better in this design.
once things are in a publishable state, I plan on writing up a pretty extensive overview of studio.FAB â€“ followed by detailed instructions and a bill of materials so you can build your own. right now though, I just wanted to make sure you got a small glimpse at whatâ€™s been happening in the studio for the past few months. http://www.stardotstudio.com/2012/05/a-small-preview-studio-fab.html definitely more to come, including:
_ linear bearings for t-slots
while you're waiting, please enjoy these M4 t-nuts I created for 25mm t-slot.  the 48mm t-nut holds 2 M4 nuts (which line up w/ the openings on a 25x50 t-slot extrustion...)

description.text:
I liked TimStough's remix of Mrcleanr6's Horga'hn model, but I wanted to align the layers with the 'carved' tool marks, avoid supports, and fit the model into a short & squat printer. The poly count has been further reduced, and a cavity has been added to the top, reducing the filament used and lowering the center of gravity.
I was able to generate gcode for this model in slic3r on a moderately provisioned pc with some auto-repaired errors, but without timing out.
Still working on the final details, planning more sanding to hide the layer lines, and wood putty for some of the gaps at the joint between the halves

This is my design for a nosepiece/nosepad (found on glasses) cover so your glasses don't get caught in your hair.

The nosepiece covers/clips on a pair of sunglasses.

General Outline of My Design Process

I designed this starting out with researching the nosepiece and physically testing out the glasses by putting them on my head. I figured out that your hair gets caught on the top part of the nosepiece and realized that's what I have to cover. I then created a mockup made out of cardboard, which helped me figure out which designs worked and which didn't. I then created a prototype which was a 3D print design that was a rougher version of the one above. It was really bulky and obtrusive but it did serve its purpose. I began to play around with the shapes of the nosepiece clip/cover more, trying to create a more comfortable design. I also tried to march the measurements of the nosepiece more precisely. I came to my final result, the design above.

I was given an assignment for my engineering class this year to design and engineer something that solves a problem in my life.  I chose creating a cover for the nosepiece on glasses that gets caught in your hair.  With the cover, the nosepieces don't get caught in your hair anymore.

title: Anet A8 frame + spot lighting with grille cover

description.text:
I added LED lighting around the frame, plus a spotlight to illuminate the print area from all around.
The LED lighting came from IKEA:

  • 1 x LEDBERG lighting strip, 3 x 25 cm strips, 10 €
  • 1 x JANSJÖ clamp spotlight, 13 €

The lighting comes with one power adapter each. To get around using extra sockets, I designed a frame to hold the power adapters together. I mounted it on top of the power supply, attached to the frame.

The wires coming with these LED lamps is very long. For neatness, cables should be cut to much smaller sections to connect the elements together, and to the power supplies.
I used 5 cm sections between the elements, and 30 cm to the power supply.

Basic soldering skills are required, to solder the wires to the lighting elements.

You need to procure 2 sockets if you want to plug the power adapters as I did. (see photos). Otherwise you could solder the wires directly to the power adapters.

The grille (3D printed) is the frame holding the adapters together. After setting it up with the wiring and the 2 adapters (see photos) I used hot-glued to stick it to the frame, on top of the power supply.

Anet A8

Doesn't Matter

Yes

0.2

100

Notes:

Building Steps

Cut 30 cm of wire from each lamp, including the plug. These will go to the power adapters.

Cut 2 x 5 cm of white wire. Use these to solder the 3 20 cm LED lighting strips together. Solder the power cable as well, to the upper-right corner of your assembly.
Glue the LED strips to the frame as shown in #2 and in #3 (photo #3 was taken from behind, so the wires going to the power are shown in the upper-left)..

Prepare the spot lamp by trimming the wire. You can disassemble the switch easily by just pulling both the top & bottom apart. Solder the 30 cm wire as shown in #4.

The power adapters are shown in #5. I hot-glued them together, but this is not required.

Print the frame, shown in #6 - #8. Ensure the power adapter fit inside, I had to trim off a bit of material around the opening to make the hole larger.

Fit the mains wire through the hole at the bottom (yes it's there ! #9 ;)

Install the power adapters inside the frame as shown in #10. They should be a snug fit.

Connect the mains wire to the 230 V power connectors as shown in #11.

Use hot glue to stick the assembly to the frame, on top of the main power supply (#12).

Finished frame with the 2 power adapters shown in #13.

Connect the wires (#14) and make them nice (#15) reusing some of that wire wrap which came from the printer, if you have any left.

This is an arm or hook to slide onto a mushroom shaped peg of a coat rack.

I needed a place to put my cycling trouser protector, that’s too wide for the standard peg. This hook should work well to hang scarfs, too. Or scarves, according to taste.

The wall side hole is sized for a peg with diameters of 8.3 mm and 16.1 mm and a thin stem of 16.8 mm.

The FreeCAD file contains a spreadsheet where the sizes can be changed. You may have to remove some of the composite shapes and re-join them. Either i missed something in FreeCAD, or i already reached the limits of what it can do, as i didn’t manage to create a nice fillet on the whole top edge of the piece in one go.

There is a bit of design history in the hook-hook folder of my github 3d printing repo.

Spinning Gyroscopic rings fidget toy.
customised in solidworks 2016.

The ring clearance and the pivot clearance are seperate dimensions.
customising the design for yourself in solidworks should be quite easy.

Notes:

Rings Seemed to spin better with less infill.

I printed two, one with 0.1 infill, the other with .7
the .7 felt nice and weighty, but the 0.1 spins for longer.

UPDATE
.7 infill is now spinning just as good if not better than the 0.1 infill, probably just needed more time to wear in.

Tight

The pivot points work best if they're nice and close together.
the ones I printed were just touching at one point in one layer at the pivot points.
This does mean it'll be a little stiff just after printing, but after moving it around, and with the help of some compressed air, it loosen up very well.

Customised

I wanted to separate the clearance values between the rings and between the pivot points.
This was due to my prints from other versions, with either the rings being too close together and rubbing on each other, or the pivot points being too loose.

The overall size of the rings was made to suit my hands.

title: Tarantula Rear Radial Fan Duct with Auto Level Mounting Space

description.text:
Rear mounted 50mm radial fan duct.

There is space for an auto level sensor to be mounted in the stock location.

The design includes internal baffles which help with bridging and diverting air flow around the ring. Check that your slicer includes them. If it doesn't don't worry, if your happy to bridge, it will still work.

There is minimal space between the bottom of the duct and the print, so make sure your bed is flat and the fan is inserted into the duct squarely or it may drag. On that, you may want to file the duct to ensure a perfect fit of the blower (I filed out the internal corners to ensure they were square).

Hope you like it!

Update
I have added a thin duct version if you don't have enough clearance under your Z-Axis gantry for the original version. The duct on the 'thin' version is 4.25mm high. I haven't tried the airflow, so if you need this version please let me know if the flow is sufficient. Thanks.

To mount the duct you will need to drill (2.5mm) and tap (for an M3, or similar imperial bolt) into the top of the x-axis carriage. This is permanent (...), but very simple. If you don't mount it firmly the duct could drag on the print/plate.

A duet wifi/ethernet case designed to attach to a right angle section of 3030 extrusions, also has countersunk holes to attach a 60mm fan for some active cooling.

The lid is a simple push fit, the bumps on one side are more pronounced than the other, as the case has lateral give just put the thicker bumps in first and then slightly flex the case to snap in the smaller bumps.

description.text:
"The Lords of the Beyond after being banished left behind a large strip of devastated land, with ghost towns, buildings, temples and a whole range of localities. Rumors that in these places existed treasures, weapons and a whole range of fantastic things, began to arrive in the ears of the people of our world.

Individuals in search of fame and fortune have decided to enter these cursed lands in search of these prizes. Organized in small groups, they enter these lands and there they face dangers. This is the premise of Scavengers, a skirmish game in the devastated lands, where you lead a group of adventurers in search of fame and fortune.

Extracted from Alabar Chronicle´s, a Scavenger Guide to Our World"

Introduction

Scavengers is a table top miniature war game for fighting skirmishes with fantasy/steampunk figures. Two players fight a small scale combat with five to ten miniatures on each side (a hero and your henchmen). The game is easy to learn and play, though there is enough depth that it will take time and experience to master.

The game was designed around three core premises.

a) You can download our 3D models or use any miniatures in their collection. Thus, the game is not specifically designed to any particular manufacturer or company. But if you like to help the game dev, please download our models! (They are free and paid...)

b) It is important that the miniatures on the table be the focus of the game. In the end, miniature gaming should be about miniatures (and fun!)

c) A large background - We´ll develop new units, histories and game scenarios. But we need your help, sending suggestions to improve the game!

I hope you like our game and have fun! Ahh, an important thing: this is the basic core rules, our idea is releasing other books to improve the game!

This is an inn, for your game table! Our gaming site is coming with our core book, game lore and a lot of new things!

Note: You don´t need a base for it.

title: Mini Drak Big fin (2 piece for smaller printers)

description.text:
All credit goes to billyd for designing the 3d printed ritewing MD fin. i just used slic3r to cut the fin into two pieces so they would fit on my Prusa mk2 print bed. A little bead of CA glues the pieces together and the seam is barely visible when installed. The seam feels as strong as the rest of the ABS. i had some slight warping which i fixed partially by staightening with a heatgun while clamping it flat. its not perfect so i printed the second fin in mirror (180 degrees on y axis) so any slight warping is reverse angle on the other fin. Small fins are in billyd's original file.

I printed with billyd's suggested settings: 15% infill, 2 bottom, 3 top layres

comments.text: Good idea! If the CA doesn't hold up let me know I can redesign from the original solid model (much easier to work with than an STL) to make the joint stronger with more area for the glue.
